[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 15.10: Hospital Resource Allocation Under Uncertainty
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Pilot · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3,000-$12,000/month (simulation + training infrastructure)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every hospital administrator has lived this nightmare: it's Tuesday afternoon, your ICU is at 94% capacity, three trauma cases just came through the ED, two OR cases are running long, and your charge nurse is calling to ask where you're putting the post-surgical patients who were supposed to transfer to med-surg but can't because med-surg is full because three discharges got delayed because transport is backed up because... you get the idea.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Hospital resource allocation is a cascading constraint satisfaction problem that changes every hour. Beds, nurses, respiratory therapists, ventilators, OR time, transport staff, isolation rooms, telemetry monitors. Every resource is finite. Every decision affects every other decision downstream. And the demand is fundamentally uncertain: you don't know when the next trauma will arrive, which patient will deteriorate, or which discharge will get delayed by a pending lab result.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The current approach at most hospitals is reactive. Charge nurses and bed coordinators make real-time decisions based on experience, gut feel, and whoever is yelling loudest. They're remarkably good at it (humans are excellent at rapid heuristic decision-making under pressure), but they're also burning out. They can't see the whole system simultaneously. They can't model the probabilistic consequences of today's bed assignment on tomorrow's surgical schedule. They optimize locally because they have to act now.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The scale of the problem is staggering. A 500-bed hospital makes hundreds of resource allocation decisions per day. Each decision interacts with dozens of constraints: patient acuity, staffing ratios, infection control requirements, equipment availability, physician preferences, regulatory requirements. A bed isn't just a bed. It's a bed in a specific unit, with specific monitoring capabilities, specific nurse-to-patient ratios, specific isolation status. Putting a patient in the "wrong" bed cascades: you might need a 1:1 sitter, a portable monitor from another unit, or a nurse floating from a department that's now short-staffed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The financial impact is measurable. ED boarding (patients waiting in the ED for an inpatient bed) costs hospitals millions annually in lost throughput, increased length of stay, and worse outcomes. Surgical cancellations due to bed unavailability cost $10,000-$50,000 per cancelled case in lost revenue. Staff overtime from poor allocation planning adds up fast. And patient outcomes suffer: studies have shown that ICU patients who experience delayed transfer to step-down units have longer overall stays.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is where reinforcement learning gets interesting. Resource allocation under uncertainty is a sequential decision problem with delayed rewards. Today's bed assignment affects tomorrow's flexibility. Holding an ICU bed open "just in case" has a cost (the patient who needs it now), but so does filling it (the patient who needs it at 3 AM). The optimal policy depends on the current state of the entire hospital, the time of day, the day of the week, the season, and the specific patient mix. No static rulebook handles this well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Reinforcement Learning for Dynamic Resource Management
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why RL Fits This Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Resource allocation under uncertainty has three properties that make it a natural RL problem:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sequential decisions with delayed consequences.** Assigning a patient to a bed right now constrains what you can do in four hours. Calling in an extra nurse costs money but prevents a potential safety issue tonight. These temporal dependencies are exactly what RL handles well. Unlike greedy optimization (which picks the best action right now), RL learns policies that balance immediate costs against future flexibility.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stochastic environment.** Demand is unpredictable. Patient arrivals follow non-stationary distributions (more traumas on weekends, more elective admissions Monday through Wednesday, seasonal respiratory surges in winter). Patient length of stay is uncertain. Complications happen. RL is designed for stochastic environments. It learns to make decisions that are robust to uncertainty, not just optimal for the expected case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **High-dimensional state space.** The "state" of a hospital at any moment includes hundreds of variables: census by unit, acuity levels, staffing levels, pending admissions, pending discharges, OR schedule, equipment availability. Classical optimization (linear programming, mixed-integer programming) struggles with this dimensionality when combined with uncertainty. Deep RL can learn value functions over high-dimensional state spaces using neural network function approximators.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The MDP Formulation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m To apply RL, you formalize the hospital as a Markov Decision Process:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **State (what the agent observes):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The state vector captures a snapshot of hospital operations. A realistic formulation might include:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Current census by unit (ICU, step-down, med-surg, telemetry, ED, OR)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Bed availability by type (standard, isolation, negative pressure, bariatric)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patient acuity distribution per unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Staffing levels by role (RN, RT, CNA, transport) vs. scheduled
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Pending admissions (ED boarders, direct admits, surgical cases in OR)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Pending discharges (confirmed, probable, unlikely today)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - OR schedule remaining for the day
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Time features (hour, day of week, month, holiday flag)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Equipment inventory (ventilators available, monitors, pumps)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Historical demand patterns for this time window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This easily reaches 200-500 continuous features. Dimensionality reduction helps (aggregating individual patients into unit-level statistics), but you need enough resolution to make useful decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Actions (what the agent decides):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Actions operate at multiple time scales:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Immediate: assign specific patient to specific bed/unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Short-term: request staff float (move nurse from one unit to another)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Short-term: activate overflow capacity (open a closed unit section)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Medium-term: adjust elective admission targets for tomorrow
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Medium-term: pre-position equipment to anticipated high-demand units
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For tractability, most implementations use a discrete action space with 10-50 actions representing common allocation decisions. Continuous action spaces (specifying exact resource quantities) are possible but harder to validate and explain.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reward (what defines success):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reward function must balance multiple competing objectives:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m reward = -w1 * ed_boarding_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          - w2 * surgical_cancellations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          - w3 * staffing_ratio_violations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          - w4 * patient_transfers (moves between units)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          - w5 * overtime_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          + w6 * discharge_before_noon_rate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m          + w7 * unit_census_balance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each weight reflects organizational priorities. A safety-net hospital might weight ED boarding heavily. A surgical center might weight OR cancellations. The weights are not learned; they're set by hospital leadership and represent policy choices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The tricky part: some rewards are immediate (a staffing ratio violation is observable now) while others are delayed (a surgical cancellation tomorrow because you filled too many beds today). RL handles this temporal credit assignment through its value function, but the delay makes learning slower and evaluation harder.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transition dynamics (how the hospital state evolves):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The hospital state transitions according to:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patient arrivals (stochastic, modeled from historical data)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patient discharges (semi-predictable, conditioned on diagnosis and LOS)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patient deterioration/improvement (stochastic, acuity-dependent)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Staff shift changes (deterministic schedule plus stochastic callouts)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - OR case completions (semi-predictable from schedule and case type)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m These dynamics are what you build into the simulation environment. The fidelity of your simulator determines the quality of your learned policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Offline vs. Online Learning: The Critical Tradeoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **You cannot do online RL in a live hospital.** Let me be unambiguous about this. You cannot explore suboptimal resource allocation strategies on real patients to gather training data. The exploration component of RL (trying things to see what happens) is incompatible with patient safety and operational requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This means all training happens offline, using one of two approaches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Approach 1: Offline RL from historical data.** You collect historical operational data (who was placed where, what happened next, what the outcomes were) and learn a policy that would have performed better than the observed decisions. This uses offline RL algorithms (Conservative Q-Learning, Implicit Q-Learning, Decision Transformer) that learn from a fixed dataset without online interaction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge: distribution shift. Your learned policy will recommend actions that weren't taken in the historical data. You have no ground truth for what would have happened if those actions had been taken. Offline RL algorithms address this with conservatism (staying close to the behavior policy), but it limits how much improvement you can achieve.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Approach 2: Simulator-based training.** You build a discrete-event simulation of hospital operations, calibrated to your hospital's historical data. The RL agent trains in this simulator, exploring freely without risk. The simulator captures arrival patterns, length-of-stay distributions, staffing models, and resource constraints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge: sim-to-real gap. Your simulator is a model of reality, not reality itself. If it's miscalibrated (patient arrivals don't match, LOS distributions are wrong, it doesn't capture seasonal effects), the policy you learn will be optimized for the wrong world. Domain randomization (training across a range of simulator parameters) helps make the policy robust to miscalibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In practice, you want both. Train primarily in simulation. Validate against historical data (would this policy have performed better on last month's actual patient flow?). Deploy with extensive guardrails and human oversight.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Safety Constraints in Hospital RL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Unlike some RL domains where constraint violations are just suboptimal, hospital resource allocation has hard constraints that cannot be violated:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Minimum staffing ratios (regulatory, not negotiable)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Isolation requirements (infection control, patient safety)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Equipment compatibility (a patient on a ventilator needs a bed with ventilator hookups)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Scope of practice (cannot assign tasks outside a provider's credential)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Maximum capacity limits (fire code, licensing)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m These must be enforced at action selection time, not just penalized in the reward. The architecture needs a constraint checker that vetoes any action violating hard constraints, regardless of what the policy network outputs. The policy learns over time not to propose infeasible actions (because they never result in reward), but the hard constraint layer is the safety guarantee.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Constrained Markov Decision Processes (CMDPs)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The formal framework for RL with constraints is the Constrained MDP. In a CMDP, you have the standard MDP objective (maximize cumulative reward) plus constraint functions that must stay below specified thresholds:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m maximize: E[Σ γ^t * r(s_t, a_t)]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m subject to: E[Σ γ^t * c_i(s_t, a_t)] ≤ d_i   for all i
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Where c_i are constraint cost functions and d_i are maximum allowable costs. For hospital RL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - c_1 might be "minutes any patient spends without adequate nurse coverage"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - c_2 might be "number of times ICU census exceeds safe capacity"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - c_3 might be "ED boarding hours exceeding 4-hour threshold"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Algorithms like Constrained Policy Optimization (CPO) and Lagrangian relaxation methods solve CMDPs by jointly optimizing the objective and satisfying constraints. In practice, you combine CMDP training with a hard constraint action mask for absolute safety limits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architecture has four major components: data ingestion, simulation environment, RL training pipeline, and decision support interface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Real-time Hospital Data] → [State Aggregator] → [Current State Vector]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                          ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Historical Data] → [Simulator Calibration] → [Hospital Simulator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                          ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                [RL Training Loop]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                          ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                [Trained Policy]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                          ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Current State Vector] → [Policy Inference] → [Constraint Checker] → [Recommendations]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                                             ↓
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                                    [Human Decision-Maker]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data ingestion** pulls real-time operational data from ADT (Admit-Discharge-Transfer) systems, nurse staffing platforms, OR scheduling systems, and equipment tracking. This feeds the state vector for inference and the historical dataset for simulator calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The simulation environment** is a discrete-event simulation of hospital operations. Patients arrive according to learned distributions. They move through the hospital (ED to inpatient, OR to PACU to floor). Length of stay follows diagnosis-specific distributions. Staff shift according to schedules. The simulator must be fast enough to run thousands of episodes for training.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The RL training pipeline** trains the policy network against the simulator. Training happens offline (batch), not in real-time. You retrain periodically (weekly or monthly) as hospital patterns change. The training loop includes constraint enforcement, reward shaping, and domain randomization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The decision support interface** presents the trained policy's recommendations to human operators (charge nurses, bed coordinators, capacity managers). This is explicitly a decision support system, not an autonomous controller. Humans see the recommendation, the reasoning (which constraints are tight, what the model predicts about future demand), and decide whether to accept it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for RL training.** SageMaker provides managed RL training with support for custom environments, multiple RL algorithms (through RLlib integration), and distributed training across multiple instances. For a complex hospital simulation environment, you need GPU instances for the policy network and CPU instances for running multiple simulator copies in parallel. SageMaker handles this orchestration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for the training pipeline.** The end-to-end flow (data extraction, simulator calibration, training, evaluation, model registration) is a multi-step workflow with conditional logic (only deploy if evaluation metrics exceed threshold). Step Functions orchestrates this cleanly with retry logic and error handling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for real-time state ingestion.** Hospital operational data arrives continuously from multiple source systems. Kinesis ingests ADT events, staffing updates, and equipment status changes in real-time, feeding the state aggregator that builds the current hospital state vector.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for state storage and action logging.** Every state observation and every recommendation (accepted or rejected) gets logged. DynamoDB's single-digit-millisecond latency supports real-time inference while its durability supports audit requirements. The time-series nature of the data maps well to DynamoDB's sort key patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for inference.** Once trained, the policy network is relatively small (a few hundred MB). Lambda can load the model and produce a recommendation in under a second given a state vector. For a decision support system that produces recommendations every 15-30 minutes, Lambda's per-invocation pricing is more economical than a persistent endpoint.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for training data and model artifacts.** Historical operational data, simulator configurations, training checkpoints, and final model artifacts all live in S3. Lifecycle policies manage the volume of training data over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Data Ingestion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A[ADT System] -->|Events| K[Kinesis Data Stream]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         B[Staffing System] -->|Updates| K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         C[OR Scheduling] -->|Cases| K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         D[Equipment Tracking] -->|Status| K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K --> SA[Lambda: State Aggregator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SA --> DDB[DynamoDB: State Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Training Pipeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         S3H[S3: Historical Data] --> CAL[SageMaker Processing:\nSimulator Calibration]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         CAL --> SIM[Custom Gym Environment:\nHospital Simulator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SIM --> TRAIN[SageMaker RL Training:\nPPO + Constraints]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         TRAIN --> EVAL[SageMaker Processing:\nOffline Evaluation]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         EVAL -->|Pass| REG[SageMaker Model Registry]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Inference
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         DDB -->|Current State| INF[Lambda: Policy Inference]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         REG -->|Model Artifact| INF
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         INF --> CC[Constraint Checker]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         CC --> REC[Recommendations API]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     REC --> UI[Capacity Dashboard]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     UI --> HUMAN[Bed Coordinator / Charge Nurse]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SF[Step Functions] -.->|Orchestrates| CAL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SF -.->|Orchestrates| TRAIN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     SF -.->|Orchestrates| EVAL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Services | SageMaker, Step Functions, Kinesis, DynamoDB, Lambda, S3, API Gateway, CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | IAM Permissions | sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob, sagemaker:CreateModel, kinesis:GetRecords, dynamodb:PutItem/GetItem, lambda:InvokeFunction, s3:GetObject/PutObject, states:StartExecution |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | BAA | Required. All operational data contains patient identifiers (room assignments, acuity levels). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Encryption | S3 SSE-KMS, DynamoDB encryption at rest, Kinesis server-side encryption, Lambda environment variable encryption |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | VPC | Training and inference in private subnets. VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker. No public internet access for PHI-containing workloads. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | CloudTrail | All API calls logged. DynamoDB streams for state change audit. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Sample Data | Synthetic hospital operational data for development. Real ADT feeds for calibration (requires data governance approval). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost Estimate | Training: ~$500-2,000 per training run (GPU instances for 8-24 hours). Inference: ~$50-200/month (Lambda invocations every 15-30 min). Data storage: ~$100-500/month. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role in This Recipe |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|-------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon SageMaker | RL model training with custom hospital simulation environment |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Step Functions | Orchestration of training, evaluation, and deployment pipeline |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon Kinesis Data Streams | Real-time ingestion of hospital operational events |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon DynamoDB | State storage, action logging, and audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Lambda | State aggregation and policy inference |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon S3 | Training data, simulator configs, model artifacts |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon API Gateway | REST endpoint for recommendation requests |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon CloudWatch | Monitoring model performance and operational metrics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Code: Pseudocode Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Step 1: Define the Hospital State Vector
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every decision starts with knowing where you are. The state aggregator collects real-time data from multiple source systems and assembles a single vector representing the current hospital state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step (or do it poorly), the policy makes decisions based on stale or incomplete information. A resource allocation recommendation based on two-hour-old census data is useless during a surge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION build_state_vector(hospital_id, timestamp):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull current census from each unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     census = GET_CENSUS_BY_UNIT(hospital_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Returns: {icu: 18/20, stepdown: 22/24, medsurg: 85/100, ...}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull current staffing vs. scheduled
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     staffing = GET_STAFFING_LEVELS(hospital_id, timestamp)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Returns: {icu_rn: 6/6, medsurg_rn: 12/14, rt: 3/4, ...}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull pending movements
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pending_admits = GET_PENDING_ADMISSIONS(hospital_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ED boarders waiting, direct admits confirmed, OR cases finishing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pending_discharges = GET_PENDING_DISCHARGES(hospital_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Confirmed (transport ordered), probable (awaiting labs), unlikely today
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull equipment availability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     equipment = GET_EQUIPMENT_STATUS(hospital_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Ventilators, monitors, pumps, isolation carts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build time features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     time_features = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hour: EXTRACT_HOUR(timestamp),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         day_of_week: EXTRACT_DOW(timestamp),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         month: EXTRACT_MONTH(timestamp),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         is_holiday: CHECK_HOLIDAY(timestamp),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         minutes_until_shift_change: CALC_SHIFT_MINUTES(timestamp)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Assemble into normalized vector
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state = CONCATENATE(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         NORMALIZE(census),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         NORMALIZE(staffing),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         NORMALIZE(pending_admits),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         NORMALIZE(pending_discharges),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         NORMALIZE(equipment),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ENCODE(time_features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN state  // Shape: [1, state_dim] where state_dim ~ 200-500
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Step 2: Build the Hospital Simulation Environment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The simulator is the heart of the system. It models hospital operations with enough fidelity to produce useful policies, but fast enough to run thousands of episodes during training.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If your simulator is miscalibrated (arrival rates are wrong, LOS distributions don't match reality), you'll learn a policy optimized for a hospital that doesn't exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CLASS HospitalSimulator:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FUNCTION __init__(config):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Load hospital-specific parameters
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.units = config.units  // [{name, capacity, type, staffing_ratio}, ...]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.arrival_model = LOAD_ARRIVAL_MODEL(config.arrival_params)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.los_model = LOAD_LOS_MODEL(config.los_params)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.staff_schedule = LOAD_STAFF_SCHEDULE(config.staff_params)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Initialize state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.clock = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.patients = []  // Active patients with unit, acuity, los_remaining
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.event_queue = PRIORITY_QUEUE()  // Upcoming events sorted by time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FUNCTION reset():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Start a new episode with random initial conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Sample initial census from historical distribution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.clock = SAMPLE_START_TIME()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.patients = SAMPLE_INITIAL_CENSUS(self.clock)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         self.event_queue = GENERATE_INITIAL_EVENTS(self.clock)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN self.get_state()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FUNCTION step(action):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Execute action (e.g., assign patient X to unit Y)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         constraint_violation = CHECK_HARD_CONSTRAINTS(action, self.state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF constraint_violation:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN self.get_state(), LARGE_NEGATIVE_REWARD, False, {violation: True}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         APPLY_ACTION(action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Advance simulation to next decision point
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHILE NOT DECISION_POINT_REACHED():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             event = self.event_queue.pop()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             self.clock = event.time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             PROCESS_EVENT(event)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Events: patient arrival, discharge, deterioration, shift change
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Calculate reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward = COMPUTE_REWARD(self.state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Check if episode is done (e.g., 24-hour horizon)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         done = (self.clock >= self.episode_end)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN self.get_state(), reward, done, {}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FUNCTION compute_reward(state, action):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= W_BOARDING * COUNT_ED_BOARDERS(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= W_CANCEL * COUNT_SURGICAL_CANCELLATIONS(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= W_RATIO * COUNT_STAFFING_VIOLATIONS(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= W_TRANSFER * COUNT_PATIENT_MOVES(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= W_OVERTIME * CALC_OVERTIME_HOURS(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward += W_BALANCE * CALC_CENSUS_BALANCE(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Step 3: Train the RL Policy with Safety Constraints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Training uses Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) with Lagrangian constraint handling. PPO is stable, well-understood, and works well with discrete action spaces. The Lagrangian approach converts hard constraints into adaptive penalty terms that the optimizer balances against the reward objective.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip constraint handling, the policy will find clever ways to game the reward (e.g., never admitting patients achieves zero boarding, but zero throughput).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION train_policy(simulator, config):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Initialize policy and value networks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     policy_net = NEURAL_NETWORK(input_dim=STATE_DIM, output_dim=ACTION_DIM)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     value_net = NEURAL_NETWORK(input_dim=STATE_DIM, output_dim=1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Initialize Lagrange multipliers for constraints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     lambda_staffing = 1.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     lambda_capacity = 1.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     lambda_boarding = 1.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR episode IN RANGE(config.num_episodes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Domain randomization: vary simulator parameters each episode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sim_params = SAMPLE_DOMAIN_RANDOMIZATION(config.domain_rand_range)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         simulator.configure(sim_params)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state = simulator.reset()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         episode_reward = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         episode_constraints = {staffing: 0, capacity: 0, boarding: 0}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         trajectory = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHILE NOT done:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Get action from policy (with exploration noise during training)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             action_probs = policy_net(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             action = SAMPLE_FROM(action_probs)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Apply action mask for hard constraints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             feasible_actions = GET_FEASIBLE_ACTIONS(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             action = MASK_AND_RESAMPLE(action_probs, feasible_actions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             next_state, reward, done, info = simulator.step(action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Track constraint costs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             episode_constraints.staffing += STAFFING_COST(state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             episode_constraints.capacity += CAPACITY_COST(state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             episode_constraints.boarding += BOARDING_COST(state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Compute augmented reward with Lagrangian penalties
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             augmented_reward = reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 - lambda_staffing * STAFFING_COST(state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 - lambda_capacity * CAPACITY_COST(state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 - lambda_boarding * BOARDING_COST(state, action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             trajectory.append({state, action, augmented_reward, next_state, done})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state = next_state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             episode_reward += reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Update policy using PPO
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UPDATE_PPO(policy_net, value_net, trajectory)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Update Lagrange multipliers (dual gradient ascent)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         lambda_staffing += LR_DUAL * (episode_constraints.staffing - THRESHOLD_STAFFING)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         lambda_capacity += LR_DUAL * (episode_constraints.capacity - THRESHOLD_CAPACITY)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         lambda_boarding += LR_DUAL * (episode_constraints.boarding - THRESHOLD_BOARDING)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Clamp multipliers to prevent instability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         lambda_staffing = MAX(0, lambda_staffing)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         lambda_capacity = MAX(0, lambda_capacity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         lambda_boarding = MAX(0, lambda_boarding)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN policy_net
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Step 4: Offline Policy Evaluation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Before deploying any learned policy, you must evaluate it against historical data. This tells you whether the policy would have performed better than actual human decisions on real scenarios.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip evaluation, you're deploying a policy trained in simulation without any evidence it works in reality.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION evaluate_policy_offline(policy, historical_episodes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Importance-weighted evaluation (off-policy)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR episode IN historical_episodes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cumulative_reward_policy = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cumulative_reward_actual = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         importance_weights = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR (state, actual_action, actual_reward) IN episode.transitions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // What would our policy have done?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             policy_action_probs = policy(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             policy_action = ARGMAX(policy_action_probs)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Importance weight for off-policy correction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // (only needed for full OPE; simplified here)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             weight = policy_action_probs[actual_action] / behavior_policy_prob(actual_action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             importance_weights.append(weight)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             cumulative_reward_actual += actual_reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Estimate policy value using weighted importance sampling
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         policy_value_estimate = WEIGHTED_IS_ESTIMATE(episode, importance_weights)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             actual_reward: cumulative_reward_actual,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             estimated_policy_reward: policy_value_estimate,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             improvement: policy_value_estimate - cumulative_reward_actual
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Aggregate results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     avg_improvement = MEAN([r.improvement FOR r IN results])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     confidence_interval = BOOTSTRAP_CI(results, alpha=0.05)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         avg_improvement: avg_improvement,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ci_lower: confidence_interval.lower,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ci_upper: confidence_interval.upper,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         episodes_evaluated: LEN(results),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pass_threshold: avg_improvement > MIN_IMPROVEMENT AND ci_lower > 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Step 5: Deploy as Decision Support with Human Override
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The trained policy produces recommendations, not commands. A human operator sees the recommendation, the reasoning, and decides whether to follow it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip the human-in-the-loop layer, you've built an autonomous hospital controller. Nobody wants that. Nobody should want that.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION generate_recommendation(hospital_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build current state
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state = build_state_vector(hospital_id, NOW())
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load latest approved policy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     policy = LOAD_MODEL(model_registry, stage="approved")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Get policy recommendation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     action_probs = policy(state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     top_actions = TOP_K(action_probs, k=3)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check hard constraints on each recommendation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     feasible_recommendations = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR action IN top_actions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         violations = CHECK_HARD_CONSTRAINTS(action, state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF NOT violations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             explanation = GENERATE_EXPLANATION(action, state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             feasible_recommendations.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 action: action,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: action_probs[action],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 explanation: explanation,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 predicted_impact: ESTIMATE_IMPACT(action, state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Log for audit and future training
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     LOG_RECOMMENDATION({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         timestamp: NOW(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state: state,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         recommendations: feasible_recommendations,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version: policy.version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN feasible_recommendations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION handle_human_decision(recommendation_id, decision):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Record whether human accepted, modified, or rejected
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     LOG_DECISION({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         recommendation_id: recommendation_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         decision: decision,  // "accepted", "modified", "rejected"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         modification_details: decision.details IF decision == "modified",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason: decision.reason IF decision == "rejected"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This data feeds back into training to improve policy alignment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter15.10-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
